        "Name of your project": "VoxBridge",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "OneVoice Guard is an offline Android two-way voice interpreter for factories and logistics sites where Vietnamese-speaking and English-speaking workers need fast communication in noisy, hands-busy, and low-connectivity environments, with future expansion planned for Mandarin Chinese and Korean.  The app captures Vietnamese or English speech on device, uses Qualcomm-optimized Whisper ASR with reliability checks for noisy audio, translates accepted transcripts with a compact local model, then verifies the translated sentence before speaking it. If safety-critical meaning from the source, such as negation, equipment names, machine numbers, hazard terms, or urgency, is missing after translation, the system repairs the translated sentence when confident or asks the speaker to repeat. After output, workers can approve the result or correct the recognized source sentence and/or translated sentence. These corrections stay on device and help future translations adapt to the same workplace domain.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Most speech translation systems optimize for fluency, but industrial communication also needs reliability. Dropping one word like \"not\", losing \"number three\", or omitting \"hazard zone\" can change a safe instruction into a dangerous one.\n\nVoxBridge adds three protections while still letting workers speak naturally. First, an ASR Reliability Guard rejects silence, noisy audio, suspicious short safety commands, and low-confidence transcripts that may be ASR hallucinations. Second, a Safety Preservation Layer compares safety-critical slots in the source and translated text. If translation loses an important slot, the system restores the missing detail only when it is clearly present in the source and can be safely inserted into the translated sentence. Third, private on-device adaptation turns approved user corrections into local memory, helping the system improve on similar future utterances, regional expressions, recurring recognition mistakes, and factory-specific terms without sending workplace data to the cloud.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "VoxBridge is a Kotlin-first offline Android system. Audio is captured with push-to-talk through AudioRecord, normalized to mono 16 kHz PCM, checked for clipping, noise level, and speech duration, then passed through VAD before ASR.\n\nThe ASR target is a Qualcomm AI Hub optimized Whisper model for Snapdragon deployment through ONNX Runtime Android with QNN Execution Provider. The project will use Qualcomm AI Hub Workbench to compile, profile, and validate the ASR path, selecting the final Whisper variant based on Android offline latency, memory, and recognition accuracy. \n\nAfter ASR, unreliable transcripts become ASK_REPEAT. Accepted transcripts are translated by a translation model selected by benchmark for Android offline latency, memory, and adequacy. The Safety Preservation Layer then checks negation, action, equipment, machine or equipment number, location, hazard, and urgency. Outputs can be model translations, verified translations, slot-restored translations, memory translations, or ask-repeat decisions.\n\nThe local correction-memory loop stores approve/edit feedback in an on-device database. Corrections are first used as hints, then promoted into reusable memory only after repeated approval or administrator review.\n\nSpoken output remains offline through cached bilingual safety audio for frequent phrases and a tested offline TTS path for dynamic text used in the demo. Evaluation logs ASR reliability, translation decisions, slot-restoration decisions, memory hits, user feedback, latency, no-speech rejection, and spoken-output status. Core metrics include WER, no-speech false positives, safety-slot preservation rate, ask-repeat rate, and end-to-end latency.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–EN",
        "Project's current development phase": "Idea",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Manufacturing",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "VoxBridge can reduce communication errors in multilingual workplaces where internet access may be unreliable and safety instructions must be understood quickly. The product is designed to preserve critical details such as negation, equipment, machine number, hazard terms, and urgency while still allowing natural speech.\n\nThis can support safer coordination around machines, conveyors, forklifts, restricted areas, power systems, loading docks, and emergency communication. The local feedback loop helps the product improve for each deployment over time while keeping sensitive workplace audio, transcripts, and corrections on device instead of depending on cloud transcription or translation.\n\nAs workers approve or correct outputs, VoxBridge can gradually adapt to local workplace language, regional expressions, recurring recognition mistakes, and frequently used phrases. This is especially useful for workers who use local terms for machines, areas, and safety instructions. Over time, the system can better recognize and translate the way people actually communicate in that factory, instead of only working well for standard or clearly pronounced speech.",
        "How could your solution evolve into a real product or dep...": "VoxBridge can evolve into an Android app or rugged handheld interpreter for factories, warehouses, and logistics centers. Companies could deploy it for safety instructions, shift coordination, onboarding, restricted-zone warnings, equipment commands, and emergency communication.\n\nFuture versions can add Vietnamese-Mandarin Chinese and Vietnamese-Korean support, company-specific terminology packs, admin-reviewed correction memory, offline model and terminology updates, and device management for factory-wide deployment. For enterprise use, VoxBridge can also provide local benchmark dashboards that help teams monitor latency, repeat-request rates, safety-preservation decisions, and frequently corrected workplace terms, so each deployment can be improved without sending sensitive workplace communication to the cloud.",
