      "luma_team": "Power Rangers",
      "project_name": "FabLingo",
      "link": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1wAB4PzAHUM7h__5a1aNLHP0QAkFTn2eWOf5sdqRypG0/edit?gid=995600960#gid=995600960",
      "blank_fields": [],
      "luma_answers": {
        "Applicant type": "Team",
        "Participant/Team details: Please fill in the template": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1wAB4PzAHUM7h__5a1aNLHP0QAkFTn2eWOf5sdqRypG0/edit?gid=995600960#gid=995600960",
        "Name of your project": "FabLingo",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "FabLingo is a standalone, fully offline wearable interpreter that enables real-time bilingual conversation between workers who speak different languages, with no internet or cloud. The entire pipeline — noise-robust speech capture, code-switch-aware speech recognition, streaming translation, and natural speech synthesis — runs on a Qualcomm Snapdragon device using the Hexagon NPU. Unlike generic translators, LexiBridge can be taught the vocabulary of each specific worksite: supervisors load or speak a short glossary of machine names, materials, and safety terms, which the device uses to recognize and translate jargon correctly. A built-in safety fast-path instantly flags critical phrases (e.g. \"stop\", \"danger\") with a haptic and visual alert before the full sentence is even translated. The result is hands-free, low-latency communication built for factories, construction sites, and logistics hubs.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Existing devices and apps (Google Translate, Pocketalk, Vasco, Timekettle) are general-purpose, mostly cloud-dependent, and fail on the three things that actually matter on a worksite. LexiBridge is built around those failure modes. First, teachable on-device terminology with no retraining: each worksite has its own jargon and heavy code-switching (Vietnamese mixed with English, Korean, or Chinese terms), so LexiBridge takes a per-site glossary — uploaded as a list or spoken once — and uses contextual biasing in the recognizer plus constrained decoding in the translator so machine names, materials, and SOP terms come out right, updating in seconds and fully offline. Second, a safety-first fast-path: a lightweight keyword-spotter detects critical safety phrases and triggers a haptic and visual alert in well under a second, independent of and faster than the full translation — something no translation device offers today. Third, it is truly offline and streaming: a noise-robust front-end plus simultaneous read/write translation deliver usable latency in noisy, low-connectivity environments where cloud tools simply stop working. In short, competitors translate general speech in good conditions; LexiBridge translates worksite speech in bad conditions and adds safety — the exact gap this challenge describes.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "The full pipeline runs on-device. (1) An audio front-end with a multi-mic array, beamforming, and a lightweight DNN speech-enhancement stage recovers accuracy under industrial noise, with voice-activity detection gating the pipeline to save power. (2) A streaming, code-switch-robust ASR uses a quantized Conformer/Whisper-class encoder — for Vietnamese we start from PhoWhisper (accent-robust, 844h) with phoneme-centric code-switch handling inspired by TSPC, and on-device contextual biasing (shallow-fusion / TCPGen-style) injects the worksite glossary. (3) Simultaneous neural MT performs streaming translation with an adaptive read/write policy (wait-k / alignment-based) to balance latency versus quality, plus terminology-constrained decoding so glossary terms translate deterministically. (4) A compact VITS-style neural TTS synthesizes natural target-language speech, played through a clip speaker or bone conduction to keep ears free for ambient safety sounds. (5) A tiny keyword-spotting model runs in parallel as the safety fast-path, firing alerts while bypassing the heavier stages. Hardware is a Qualcomm Snapdragon platform (e.g. QCS6490 / 8-series) using the Hexagon NPU, with models pulled and optimized from the Qualcomm AI Hub, compiled via QNN, and quantized to INT8/INT4 (encoder a16w8, as in Qualcomm's on-device Whisper reference). Methodology: synthetic industrial-noise augmentation at controlled SNR for ASR robustness, per-domain glossary construction, and evaluation on WER (clean and noisy), translation BLEU/COMET, end-to-end latency (target <2s; safety alert <300ms), real-time factor, and power draw — with field data collected across the prototype and field-testing phases.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–EN, VN–CN",
        "Project's current development phase": "Idea",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Manufacturing",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "Fablingo attacks communication inequality directly: only about 5% of Vietnamese workers are proficient in English, while 87% of FDI companies require a foreign language — a gap that limits safety, productivity, skills transfer, and career mobility. By removing the language barrier instantly and offline, LexiBridge improves workplace safety through its real-time safety fast-path, raises productivity by cutting miscommunication during setup, maintenance, and handover, accelerates skills transfer from foreign technicians to local workers, and expands career mobility for workers who cannot afford years of language training. The impact is measurable as fewer safety incidents, faster onboarding, reduced rework and defects, and greater worker access to better-paying roles.",
        "How could your solution evolve into a real product or dep...": "The go-to-market is B2B to manufacturers and contractors: sell or lease the device per worker, paired with a subscription to a site-glossary management portal where admins push approved terminology, safety phrases, and language packs to a whole fleet of devices, all syncing offline. A licensable Edge Interpreter SDK lets the engine ship inside partners' existing hardware — earmuffs and other PPE, helmets, handhelds, or factory intercoms — and integrate with safety and MES systems. The expansion path adds language pairs (the pipeline is language-agnostic), then new verticals such as healthcare, public services, and tourism. Snapdragon plus the Qualcomm AI Hub gives a clear route from prototype to a manufacturable reference design, and the offline-by-design model means zero per-translation cloud cost — strong unit economics at fleet scale.",
        "Upload your pitch deck": "nan",
        "Share a demo video or prototype link": "nan",
        "Provide your GitHub or project repository link": "nan"
      },
