        "Participant/Team details: Please fill in the template": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1v-fRmrWothm6uuawoJlqjEdokRHDmuMS2LHc8MmP9TQ/edit?gid=0#gid=0",
        "Name of your project": "Vo2",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "Vo2 is a fully offline, real-time speech-to-speech translation solution designed for edge devices powered by Qualcomm Snapdragon hardware. Unlike cloud-based translators, Vo2 processes all data locally, ensuring low latency, enhanced privacy, and reliable operation even without an internet connection.  The system is built on a cascaded AI pipeline consisting of three stages: Speech-to-Text (STT), Machine Translation (MT), and Text-to-Speech (TTS). Spoken input is first converted into text, translated into the target language, and then synthesized back into natural speech. In its first phase, Vo2 supports bidirectional Vietnamese–English translation, while the architecture is designed to scale seamlessly to additional languages such as Mandarin and Korean without requiring major structural changes.  To enable a truly hands-free experience, Vo2 incorporates an always-listening mechanism powered by the lightweight Silero Voice Activity Detection (VAD) model. With a footprint of approximately 1 MB in ONNX format, the VAD efficiently filters background noise and activates the translation pipeline only when human speech is detected, minimizing unnecessary computation and power consumption.  The ultimate goal of Vo2 is to deliver near-instant multilingual communication on edge devices. Although current development benchmarks on CPU-based environments show processing times of approximately 5–6 seconds due to testing limitations and synthetic audio artifacts, optimization on Qualcomm Snapdragon hardware is expected to reduce end-to-end translation latency to under 0.5 seconds, enabling natural, real-time conversations across language barriers.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Vo2 introduces a set of innovations that enable practical, real-time offline speech translation on edge devices. At its core is a Unified Multilingual Translation Engine powered by a single NLLB-200-distilled-600M model. Unlike conventional approaches that require separate translation models for each language pair, Vo2 supports multiple language directions within a single architecture. This reduces deployment complexity, simplifies maintenance, and lowers the overall memory footprint by approximately 40%, while providing a scalable foundation for future language expansion.\n\nThe system is built with an edge-native, NPU-first architecture specifically optimized for Qualcomm Snapdragon platforms. Using ONNX Runtime and the Qualcomm Neural Network (QNN) Execution Provider, Vo2 leverages the Qualcomm Hexagon NPU to accelerate AI workloads directly on-device. Compared with CPU-based execution, this approach is projected to achieve 10–20× faster inference performance, enabling low-latency translation while maintaining privacy and minimizing power consumption.\n\nTo deliver a seamless user experience, Vo2 features zero-touch interaction through an always-on listening mechanism. A lightweight voice activity detection module continuously monitors incoming audio in 32 ms chunks, instantly detecting speech while filtering background noise. A 150 ms pre-roll buffer preserves the beginning of each utterance, ensuring that initial phonemes are not lost and eliminating the need for push-to-talk controls.\n\nFurthermore, Vo2 employs a streaming pipeline architecture that allows speech recognition, translation, and speech synthesis to operate concurrently. The STT module can begin transcribing before a speaker finishes talking, the translation engine processes partial transcripts in real time, and the TTS component starts generating speech before the final translation is fully completed. By overlapping these stages, Vo2 significantly reduces perceived latency and enables natural, conversational multilingual communication in real-world environments.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "Vo2 is powered by a carefully optimized suite of edge AI models with a total deployment footprint of approximately 727 MB. The system begins with Silero VAD v5, a lightweight 1 MB ONNX model responsible for continuously monitoring the environment and detecting human speech while filtering background noise. Once speech is detected, a quantized Whisper-tiny model (39 MB ONNX INT8) performs multilingual speech recognition. To further improve Vietnamese transcription quality, particularly when handling synthetic audio, future iterations will integrate PhoWhisper as a specialized enhancement layer.\n\nFor machine translation, Vo2 utilizes the NLLB-200-distilled-600M model (600 MB ONNX INT8), enabling multilingual translation across multiple language pairs through a single unified architecture. The translated text is then converted back into natural speech using Piper TTS, a lightweight text-to-speech engine with a footprint ranging from approximately 27 MB to 60 MB depending on the selected voice model. Together, these components deliver a fully offline speech-to-speech translation pipeline optimized for deployment on edge devices.\n\nThe solution is designed for premium edge computing platforms such as the Qualcomm Snapdragon X Elite and Snapdragon 8 Gen 3, leveraging their dedicated NPUs that provide between 50 and 70 TOPS of AI compute performance. Through aggressive model optimization and efficient runtime management, Vo2 targets a peak memory usage of approximately 1.5 GB, allowing the entire system to operate comfortably within a typical 4 GB hardware constraint.\n\nTo ensure both accuracy and responsiveness, Vo2 employs a rigorous evaluation framework. Translation quality is measured using COMET as the primary metric and BLEU as a secondary benchmark, complemented by human Mean Opinion Score (MOS) evaluations to assess speech naturalness and pronunciation quality. System responsiveness is evaluated through Real-Time Factor (RTF), targeting a value below 1.0, as well as end-of-speech to start-of-audio latency measurements. Performance validation is conducted using widely recognized datasets, including LibriSpeech for speech recognition, OPUS-100 for machine translation, and CoVoST2 for end-to-end speech translation benchmarking.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–EN, VN–CN",
        "Project's current development phase": "Prototype",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Education",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "Vo2 aims to break language barriers in education by enabling real-time, offline speech translation directly on edge devices. Students and educators from different linguistic backgrounds can communicate more effectively without requiring internet access, making learning more inclusive and accessible.\n\nBy providing fast, private, and reliable multilingual communication, Vo2 can support international classrooms, online learning, academic collaborations, and educational opportunities in regions with limited connectivity. Our goal is to ensure that language differences do not prevent students from accessing knowledge, participating in discussions, or connecting with others around the world.",
        "How could your solution evolve into a real product or dep...": "nan",
