        "Applicant type": "Team",
        "Participant/Team details: Please fill in the template": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1-Cg-BsijDYBxzxjnTiDVdVggLQvtd5OlFufO6zyEbjE/edit?usp=sharing",
        "Name of your project": "ViKo",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "ViKo is an edge-AI communication system that understands language, context, and urgency — designed for manufacturing environments where clarity, speed, and safety are critical.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Today, factory floors coordinate through walkie-talkies — but walkie-talkies don't translate. When a Korean supervisor needs to instruct a Vietnamese worker, teams fall back on gestures, broken phrases, or a bilingual colleague pulled from their own work. Personal translation apps help — but they were built for individuals, not factory floors. No team broadcast. No safety protocols. No hands-free operation.\nPowered by edge AI running fully on-device on Qualcomm Snapdragon, ViKo was designed for exactly this gap. It goes beyond word-for-word translation — preserving the intent behind indirect Korean instructions, handling honorifics and Vietnamese kinship pronouns, and delivering it all through a screen-free wearable that reaches every worker across every zone. No internet. No phone in hand. No learning curve.\nAnd at its core, ViKo is safety-first. Pre-verified emergency codes broadcast instantly. SOS triggers with location in under two seconds. Every safety briefing logged, every shift.\nViKo doesn't just translate language. It translates intent, hierarchy, and urgency — purpose-built for environments where miscommunication costs more than time.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "ViKo is built as a three-stage pipeline that runs entirely on a Qualcomm Snapdragon edge platform (such as the QCS6490). Audio first goes through speech recognition (ASR), which also senses the speaker's emotional tone (SER). The recognized text is then translated with context taken into account (context-aware-translation), and the translation is turned back into speech (TTS). All three stages run locally on the Snapdragon edge device using quantized models from Qualcomm AI Hub, so the system does not connect to the cloud or the internet at any point.\n\nThe wearable is designed to be cheap, light, and screen-free. An ESP32 board handles only input and output, an INMP441 microphone captures the audio, a MAX98357A amplifier plays audio back through a small speaker, and an LED and haptic motor show status, all powered by a full-shift LiPo battery. No AI runs on the wearable. The recognition, translation, and speech generation all happen on the Snapdragon edge unit.\n\nThe translation stage is shaped by the fact that there is very little Vietnamese-Korean parallel data to train on. Instead of translating word for word, it aims to carry the speaker's intent, which includes choosing the right Korean honorific level and adjusting Vietnamese kinship pronouns that do not map directly. Three mechanisms sit alongside it, an admin-managed glossary that lets specific factory terms pass through without being translated, and a set of preset phrases that have been checked by a human and are used directly instead of being generated by the model. \n\nSafety-critical messages are handled separately and do not use live translation. Each emergency maps to a preset code, and triggering it plays a pre-recorded, already-translated message on every device at the same time. Because the audio is prepared in advance, there is no translation step at the moment of the emergency.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–KR",
        "Project's current development phase": "Prototype",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Manufacturing",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "Our solution can make daily communication in the factory much safer and smoother. Vietnamese workers and Korean supervisors would no longer have to rely on guessing, hand signals, or waiting for someone to translate, especially in noisy or low-internet factory environments.\nThe main impact is on safety. Workers can understand urgent instructions right away, confirm that they understood safety briefings, and send an SOS alert if something goes wrong. For emergencies like fire, gas leaks, or evacuation, preset messages can be sent instantly without waiting for AI translation.\nIt also helps workers feel more confident and respected. They can ask questions, understand instructions, and do their jobs without language barrier. For factories, this means fewer mistakes, faster coordination, better safety records, and a more inclusive workplace.",
        "How could your solution evolve into a real product or dep...": "ViKo's path to real deployment starts with a factory pilot — partnering directly with Korean-owned manufacturing facilities in Vietnam's major industrial zones such as Binh Duong and Dong Nai, where the Vietnamese–Korean communication gap is most acute. A controlled pilot with real workers and supervisors generates the accuracy benchmarks, safety response data, and worker adoption metrics needed to validate the system beyond a prototype environment.\nFrom there, ViKo scales as a complete B2B package — the wearable device, the manager app, and optional network infrastructure support for factories without existing local WiFi coverage. Factories license the system fleet-wide, provisioned and managed by HR or Safety Officers rather than requiring individual worker onboarding. The company-issued, screen-free device sidesteps the personal phone ban that blocks every competing solution from entering secure production floors.\nAs the translation model matures and training data grows, ViKo expands to additional language pairs — Vietnamese–English and beyond — and into broader Southeast Asian manufacturing markets facing the same multilingual workforce dynamics. The safety compliance layer, which logs briefing confirmations and incident history on every shift, evolves into a standalone value proposition for enterprise clients navigating labor safety regulations.\nThe long-term vision is not a translation device. It's the communication infrastructure layer for the multilingual factory floor.",
