        "Applicant type": "Individual",
        "Participant/Team details: Please fill in the template": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1Fmt-i0gWN2wLZcPNMyicX8jv9qE5s9wBflPMYkYkWLg/edit?usp=sharing",
        "Name of your project": "ISEE",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "A real-time, bi-directional Speech-to-Speech translation system designed to operate 100% offline (Edge AI) on mid-range Android mobile devices. It is specifically engineered to eliminate language barriers between Vietnamese workers and foreign experts in high-tech agriculture, manufacturing, and logistics environments where internet connectivity is unstable, restricted, or unavailable.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Our core innovation lies in solving the \"hallucination\" and latency problems of modern Neural Machine Translation (NMT) in specialized industries, while running entirely on low-end hardware:\n\nTranslation Memory (TM) Injection: Instead of using a monolithic End-to-End model (like SeamlessM4T) which is too heavy (>4GB RAM), we use a modular pipeline. This allows us to inject an offline SQLite B-Tree indexed Translation Memory between the ASR and MT steps. It performs exact and fuzzy (Levenshtein) matching for domain-specific jargon in <5ms, guaranteeing 100% accuracy for critical technical terms (e.g., hydroponic metrics, mechanical parts) without AI hallucinations.\nExtreme Resource Optimization: By utilizing INT8 quantization and Non-autoregressive models, our entire AI pipeline consumes only ~1.1GB of RAM, achieving sub-second (<1.0s) translation latency on a mid-range smartphone (e.g., Galaxy A53), making it highly accessible and affordable for blue-collar deployments.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "Hardware: Mid-range Android smartphones (Targeting Exynos 1280 / Snapdragon 7 series, 8GB RAM).\nSystem Architecture: An Android Native app (Kotlin) handles UI, Audio I/O, and continuous listening via Foreground Services with Wakelocks. A C++ Orchestrator (via JNI) manages memory pooling and parallel execution of the AI pipeline to ensure ultra-low latency.\nAI Pipeline (100% On-Device):\nVAD: Silero VAD (ONNX Runtime) for noise filtering.\nASR: SenseVoice Small (INT8, ONNX) - utilizing Non-autoregressive CTC for fast transcription (~70-100ms latency).\nDomain Filter: SQLite Translation Memory.\nMT: NLLB-200 Distilled 600M (INT8, CTranslate2 with ARM NEON SIMD).\nTTS: Piper TTS / VITS (ONNX) for fast synthesis.\nMethodology: 100% Edge AI processing without any cloud APIs, ensuring absolute data privacy and offline reliability.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–EN, VN–CN",
        "Project's current development phase": "Prototype",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Manufacturing",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "Break Technical Language Barriers: Enable seamless, accurate communication of complex technical instructions between local workers and foreign engineers/managers.\nImprove Workplace Safety & Productivity: Provide a hands-free, continuous-listening translation tool that prevents costly misunderstandings in fast-paced or hazardous environments.\nDemocratize AI Access: Bring state-of-the-art AI translation to offline, blue-collar environments using affordable mid-range mobile devices, without requiring expensive internet infrastructure or cloud API subscriptions.",
        "How could your solution evolve into a real product or dep...": "The solution is designed for enterprise mass deployment (B2B). Companies can deploy the app on standard company-issued rugged smartphones. IT administrators can push offline updates to the SQLite Translation Memory database (via local transfer or MDM) to customize the vocabulary for specific factories or farms. Future evolutions include integration with Bluetooth earpieces with advanced noise-cancellation (Acoustic Echo Cancellation) for completely hands-free operation in noisy industrial environments.",
