        "Applicant type": "Team",
        "Participant/Team details: Please fill in the template": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1l4buI9Q_O3Hu2I6hweCmh6FNpNgotTFKJtytwRMDqw4/edit?gid=995600960#gid=995600960",
        "Name of your project": "EduVoice Translator",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "Our project proposes a real-time multilingual speech translation system for educational environments. The system captures spoken input, transcribes it using fine-tuned ASR models such as Qwen3-ASR and Nemotron-ASR, translates the recognized text with GLM-based language models, and plays back natural speech output using OmniVoice TTS. The solution is designed to support Vietnamese–English, Vietnamese–Chinese, and Vietnamese–Korean communication in classrooms, seminars, online courses, and academic events. In addition to the cascaded ASR–translation–TTS pipeline, our team is also researching end-to-end speech-to-speech models such as Qwen3-Omni to further improve latency, naturalness, and real-time interaction quality.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Our solution is innovative because it combines a practical cascaded speech translation pipeline with research on end-to-end speech-to-speech models. Instead of relying on a single generic translation tool, we fine-tune ASR models such as Qwen3-ASR and Nemotron-ASR for multilingual speech recognition, use GLM-based models for context-aware translation, and generate natural target-language audio with OmniVoice TTS. This allows the system to be optimized for Vietnamese-centered educational scenarios, including classroom conversations, academic terms, mixed-language speech, and real-time learning environments.\n\nIn addition, our team is exploring speech-to-speech models such as Qwen3-Omni to reduce latency and improve natural interaction quality. This hybrid direction makes our solution different from conventional text-based translation apps, as it focuses on real-time, spoken, multilingual communication for education with the potential to evolve from a modular demo into a more seamless speech-to-speech product.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "Our technical approach is based on a modular real-time speech translation architecture. The system first captures live audio from the user and applies audio preprocessing, including noise reduction, voice activity detection, and speech segmentation. The processed speech is then transcribed by fine-tuned ASR models such as Qwen3-ASR and Nemotron-ASR, which we adapt for Vietnamese, English, Chinese, and Korean speech, with a focus on educational and academic contexts.\n\nAfter transcription, the recognized text is passed to a GLM-based translation module to generate accurate and context-aware translations. This module is designed to handle classroom conversations, academic terminology, mixed-language input, and domain-specific vocabulary. The translated text is then converted back into natural speech using OmniVoice TTS, allowing users to hear the translated output in real time.\n\nThe overall system includes audio input, streaming ASR, translation, TTS, and a user-facing interface for web or mobile use. For development and deployment, we use GPU-based servers to fine-tune and optimize the models, while the demo system is designed to run with low latency for real-time interaction. In parallel, our team is researching end-to-end speech-to-speech models such as Qwen3-Omni to further reduce latency, preserve speaking style, and improve the naturalness of multilingual communication.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–EN, VN–CN",
        "Project's current development phase": "Working demo",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Education",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "We expect our solution to reduce language barriers in education, research, and international collaboration by making multilingual communication more accessible, natural, and efficient. By enabling real-time speech translation between Vietnamese, English, Chinese, and Korean, the system can help students, teachers, researchers, and international participants communicate more effectively in classrooms, seminars, online courses, academic events, and cross-border training programs.\n\nBeyond classroom learning, the solution can also be applied to live translation for scientific seminars, international conferences, workshops, business meeting rooms, research discussions, and hybrid events. It can support real-time interpretation for speakers and audiences, provide multilingual subtitles or voice output, and help participants follow discussions without needing a human interpreter in every session.\n\nThe solution can support Vietnamese students and researchers in accessing international lectures and academic exchanges, while also helping foreign students, experts, and partners participate more easily in Vietnamese educational and professional environments. It can improve inclusion, collaboration, and knowledge sharing across different language backgrounds. In the long term, we expect the project to contribute to more open and connected education, research, and global communication, where language is no longer a major obstacle to learning, teaching, discussion, and cooperation.",
