        "Participant/Team details: Please fill in the template": "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1tNuodeQX4E6HZkUE99W_Krdd7g-nkytVUbm4LQUsiek/edit?usp=sharing",
        "Name of your project": "molink",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "Project molink (by team mozero) is a standalone, wearable Edge AI translation device engineered specifically for frontline workers in industrial and blue-collar environments. Designed to operate 100% offline, it delivers real-time, bi-directional Speech-to-Speech translation. By removing the dependency on cloud connectivity and smartphones, molink enables seamless, hands-free communication between foreign management and local workers on noisy factory floors, construction sites, and logistics hubs.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "Existing translation tools are fundamentally unsuited for industrial environments: they rely heavily on stable internet (often unavailable in warehouses), require cloud processing (causing unnatural communication latency), and demand the use of a smartphone (which occupies hands and is frequently banned on factory floors for safety reasons).\n\nmolink is innovative because it shifts the entire translation pipeline to the Edge. It is a dedicated, hands-free wearable (e.g., a smart badge or earpiece) that processes speech instantly via on-device NPUs. Furthermore, it integrates a specialized acoustic pipeline designed to filter out heavy industrial background noise and accurately capture spoken language without internet access, ensuring safe and continuous workflow.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "The system architecture focuses on low-latency, high-accuracy processing strictly on Edge hardware (leveraging Qualcomm Snapdragon platforms via Qualcomm AI Hub).\n\nHardware: A lightweight, ruggedized wearable device equipped with a directional noise-canceling microphone array to isolate voice in high-decibel environments.\n\nSystem Design & AI Models (The Offline Pipeline):\n\nOn-device STT (Speech-to-Text): Utilizing highly quantized, lightweight speech recognition models optimized for the NPU.\n\nText Normalization & Correction Module: Before translation, the raw STT output passes through an embedded text correction pipeline (inspired by architectures like PhoBERT/ViT5, but optimized for Edge via INT8 quantization). This module restores punctuation and corrects spelling with word-level confidence, ensuring the downstream translation model receives contextually clean input.\n\nEdge Translation: A compiled, quantized LLM handles the cross-lingual translation locally.\n\nOn-device TTS (Text-to-Speech): A fast-response synthesizer delivers the translated audio directly to the user's earpiece or speaker.\n\nMethodology: We will heavily utilize quantization and model compilation techniques to ensure the three-stage pipeline (STT -> Translate -> TTS) runs concurrently with minimal memory footprint and battery consumption.",
        "Expected language pair to support": "VN–EN, VN–CN, VN–KR",
        "Project's current development phase": "Idea",
        "Real-world use case or industry your solution be applied": "Manufacturing",
        "What impact do you expect your solution to create?": "Workplace Safety: Drastically reduce industrial accidents caused by misunderstood instructions.\n\nProductivity & Efficiency: Eliminate the downtime spent bridging communication gaps, speeding up skills transfer and daily operations.\n\nSocial & Economic Mobility: Empower the 95% of Vietnamese workers who lack foreign language proficiency to confidently collaborate with international management, removing a hidden barrier to career advancement in the globalized economy.",
