        "Name of your project": "VIPER",
        "Briefly describe your proposed solution": "VIPER (Vietnamese Instant Processing Edge Receiver) is an on-device Vietnamese speech recognition system optimized for edge deployment. The solution benchmarks and selects lightweight ASR models that can run locally with low latency, without relying on cloud inference, while maintaining practical transcription accuracy for real-world voice workflows.",
        "What makes your solution innovative or different from exi...": "The project focuses on a measurement-first ASR pipeline for edge devices. Instead of assuming a large model is best, we benchmark multiple Vietnamese ASR models under the same real audio dataset and compare accuracy, latency, realtime factor, and model size. The current result identifies PhoWhisper-tiny CT2 as a strong edge runtime candidate and PhoWhisper-small CT2 as a quality baseline, enabling a clear tradeoff between speed and accuracy.",
        "Describe your technical approach": "I use a modular ASR benchmarking pipeline built around real Vietnamese WAV samples and reference transcripts. The system evaluates ASR models using WER, CER, latency, P95 latency, model size, and realtime factor.\n\nCurrent tested models include faster-whisper tiny/base/small and PhoWhisper CT2 variants. The main edge candidate is PhoWhisper-tiny CT2, running with CTranslate2 INT8 on CPU. The quality baseline is PhoWhisper-small CT2.\n\nThe methodology is:\n1. collect real audio samples,\n2. run real ASR inference locally,\n3. compare transcripts against reference text,\n4. measure accuracy and runtime performance,\n5. choose separate models for quality baseline and edge runtime,\n6. prepare domain-specific benchmark data for future tuning and deployment.",
